The paper deals with the computation of the Shapley value for network centrality, which is a concept that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The most likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), as the paper explicitly mentions social and organizational networks, biological networks, and communication networks as examples of real-world applications. The second most likely category is cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), as the Shapley value is a well-known concept in game theory and the paper explicitly mentions its use in coalitional games. The third likely category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture), as the paper deals with the topology of the Western States Power Grid and a collaboration network from the field of astrophysics. The fourth likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), as the paper develops efficient algorithms for computing the Shapley value-based centrality. The fifth likely category is cs.SOC (Computers and Society), as the paper deals with social networks and their centrality measures.
